node.title: Rendering top and bottom boundary set on a stacked mesh
node.bodyText:
Issue Description
Hello. I've been trying to get an axial stack of hexagonal blocks with the top boundary set(max z) and the bottom boundary set(min z) separately defined. Looking up the StackGenerator documentation, I thought I could achieve that with front_boundary and back_boundary option.
[Mesh]
    [hex]
        type = PolygonConcentricCircleMeshGenerator
        num_sides = 6
        num_sectors_per_side = '2 2 2 2 2 2'
        ring_radii = '0.01 0.015'
        ring_intervals = '1 1'
        ring_block_ids = '11 12'
        polygon_size = 0.02
        background_block_ids = 70
        quad_center_elements = True
    []
    [extrude]
        type = MeshExtruderGenerator
        input = hex
        extrusion_vector = '0 0 .70'
    []
    [stack_them]
        type = StackGenerator
        inputs = 'extrude extrude extrude'
        dim = 3
        front_boundary=front
        back_boundary=back
        show_info = True
    []
[]

But this did not create any boundary set named front or back in the resulting mesh. I got the same results when I tried with top_boundary and bottom_boundary.
The next approach I took was using SideSetsAroundSubdomainGenerator:
[Mesh]
    [hex]
        type = PolygonConcentricCircleMeshGenerator
        num_sides = 6
        num_sectors_per_side = '2 2 2 2 2 2'
        ring_radii = '0.01 0.015'
        ring_intervals = '1 1'
        ring_block_ids = '11 12'
        polygon_size = 0.02
        background_block_ids = 70
        quad_center_elements = True
    []
    [extrude]
        type = MeshExtruderGenerator
        input = hex
        extrusion_vector = '0 0 .70'
    []
    [bot_side]
        type = SideSetsAroundSubdomainGenerator
        input = extrude
        new_boundary = bottom
        replace = True
        normal = '0 0 -1'
        external_only = True
        block = '70'
        output=True
    []
    [top_side]
        type = SideSetsAroundSubdomainGenerator
        input = extrude
        new_boundary = top
        replace = True
        normal = '0 0 1'
        external_only = True
        block = '70'
        output=True
    []
    [stack_them]
        type = StackGenerator
        inputs = 'bot_side extrude top_side'
        dim = 3
        show_info = True
    []
[]

Yes.
I dont think we rely under the hood on the StitchedMG but it s the same requirement

OR if you have custom treatment (eg not regular kernels)

@GiudGiud
Thanks for all the answers! It seems AdvancedExtruderGenerator works quite well w/ ParsedGenerateSideset

node.title: Assigning and updating material property to an element
node.bodyText:
Dear all,
Hope you are doing well.
I wanted to see if we can assign a property to a block, and it gets updated in each element. To make it clear, consider a two region system which in the right-hand side we have a solution which its property (such as density, viscosity, etc.) is dependent on the gas concentration which is injected. I saw a similar question #20334 but I wanted to check if I need to write the material property myself or it has been added.
Best regards,
Sina

Hello
This is actually the default for material properties, they are computed for every quadrature point even.
Constant or constant per-block are optimizations to compute the material properties less-often.
If your material property definition is simple enough to write in an anaytical expression, you could consider using a ParsedMaterial to try it out, with any local variable dependencies. And then you can use the output parameter of the Material to look at its variation in the exodus file
Guillaume

Dear @GiudGiud
Thanks for your reply. I checked the ParsedMaterial as you said and that's exactly what I needed. My question is that how I can pass this calculated material as a function? I get the property that I need for example density, now I need to pass it to my fluid property module which accepts functions. Or better to ask how I can use this property and not only see it's change in the output. Sorry if it is a basic question.
Thanks.
Sina

Which FluidProperty object are you trying to use?
Functions are not supposed to depend on variables, only on time and space.
However, if the fluid property object queries the functions with x = temperature for example, this can work.
It's what this does:
https://mooseframework.inl.gov/source/userobjects/TemperaturePressureFunctionFluidProperties.html

I am using TemperaturePressureFunctionFluidProperties as you mentioned. It accepts functions as input, so I was wondering if I can pass the property calculated by ParsedMaterial which is dependent on the variable to my fluid property. If this cannot be done, do you have any other suggestion?

Oh then you should use ParsedFunctions.
Please be careful when writing down the expressions
x = temperature
y = Pressure
anything else wont be correct

Thank you for your quick reply dear @GiudGiud. Just to double check then, there is no way to pass a variable-dependent material to the fluid properties to update density, vicosity, and etc? and I need to write my own material and fluid property? Thank you in advance for your time.

Nope, no way to pass a material property to a fluid property right now.
It would not be hard to do if you want to add it.
You do not need to write your own material & fluid property if you are willing to use
TemperaturePressureFunctionFluidProperties + ParsedFunctions
or any of the other pre-made FluidProperties

Unfortunatly, TemperaturePressureFunctionFluidProperties + ParsedFunctions or other FluidProperties do not work for me or I could not find a sutable one. I need to only write a FluidProperty which accepts the ParsedMaterial. I appreciate if you have any advice or similar work suggestion to look at. Thanks.
Can you write down your fluid properties here as analytical expressions? I can try to write the ParsedFunctions for you

Oh thank you. I do not have special analytical expression in my mind just wanted to check to see if it works and apply it later.
Here is what I did. I know that you mentioned TemperaturePressureFunctionFluidProperties only works for temperature and pressure correctly but I passed the saturation and it almost gives what I want. However, instead of changing the property at the element that saturation reaches, it changes the whole block. The ParsedMaterial that you mentioned do it right.
Here is my input file.
https://github.com/sinaomrani96/Material-property/blob/main/input.i
Thanks.

ok so the constant are fine as they are, you do not need to specify the symbol_names/vars.
If you have pressure OR temperature dependence, as I mentioned you can use x and y in the function expression.
However, for the pore pressure there's no solution with ParsedFunctions
Creating a new fluid properties that retrieves other material properties will be the way to go if your other objects expert a FluidProperties input

Dear @GiudGiud,
Hope you are doing well.
I followed your instruction, and when I compile I get the following error:
error: cannot convert 'const MaterialProperty' to 'libMesh::Real' {aka 'double'} in return
436 |   return _viscosity1;
|          ^~~~~~~~~~~
|          |
|          const MaterialProperty
Would you please give me an insight into fixing this?
Thanks.
Sina

Try return _viscosity1[_qp]
this retrieves the material property at the quadrature point
also an issue here, the material property must be a reference, not a value
so in the header you need
Const MaterialProperty & _viscosity1

Dear @GiudGiud,
Thanks for your quick reply. I tried to retrieves the material property at the quadrature point as you mentioned and _viscosity1[_qp] gave me the following error:
error: '_qp' was not declared in this scope; did you mean '_cp'?
436 |   return _viscosity1[_qp];
|                      ^~~
|                      _cp
I changed it to _viscosity1[_cp], and it compiles but when I run my simulation it does not converge at the very beginning.
I run it in debug mode and I get:
Assertion `i < _size' failed
Access out of bounds in MooseArray (i: 4194 size: 216)
at /home/sinaomrani/projects/moose/framework/build/header_symlinks/MooseArray.h, line 276
I appreciate it if you have any suggestion. Sorry if this is a basic question.

in which routine is this?
Can you share the code?
_cp is not an index as far as I know.

I am using PorousFlow, and created these two based on SimlpeFluidProperties, and substituting viscosity.
https://github.com/sinaomrani96/Material-property

yeah this isnt going to work..
The fluid property doesn't know the indexing into material properties. So it can't retrieve them.
What's the expression for viscosity?
Oh. I do not have any specific expression in mind, just wanted to connect the viscosity to a variable which I need later. So, what is your suggestion so I can proceed with this?
is this variable pressure, temperature or pore pressure?
Actually it is gas saturation and pressure.

Are these used in porous flow routinely?
I m thinking there will be a better base class to add your new property there (mu(p, sat))
@cpgr for guidance please
as you can see in SimpleFP and in most properties in the fluid properties module, properties are either:
property(p,T) or property(specific energy, specific volume)
Yes I guess. I will wait to see if @cpgr has a suggestion. You are correct. I am trying to find a better base class. Thanks for your help.

It might be because it is too early in the morning, but I'm not sure exactly what you are trying to do? Is viscosity a nonlinear variable in your model? I'm struggling to see how it depends on saturation?
In any case, the FluidProperties module doesn't really know about variables or the mesh, so probably isn't the right place for this.
If you are using porous flow, could you just make your own fluid properties material (inherit from PorousFlowSingleComponentFluid) and swap out the viscosity calculation with your viscosity variable?
So this bit
(*_viscosity)[_qp] = _fp.mu_from_p_T(_porepressure[_qp][_phase_num] * _pressure_to_Pascals,
                                         _temperature[_qp] + _t_c2k) /
                         _pressure_to_Pascals / _time_to_seconds;

might become simply
(*_viscosity)[_qp] = _viscosity1[_qp]

while the rest of the properties come from a fluid properties user object like normal?

Dear @cpgr, good morning then :)))
My viscosity is actually dependent on the gas saturation which is a variable and pressure which is also a variable. So, I used a ParsedMaterial to get this and would like to pass it to viscosity.
I tested your suggestion and I face this error that I cannot fix.
error: 'getMaterialProperty' was not declared in this scope; did you mean 'ADMaterialProperty'?
   34 |     _viscosity1(getMaterialProperty<Real>("viscosity1"))
      |                 ^~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
      |                 ADMaterialProperty

Should I add or modify something else?
getMaterialProperty<Real>

Dear @GiudGiud,
getMaterialProperty<Real> also did not work but  _viscosity1(this->template getMaterialProperty<Real>("viscosity1")) worked and compiled. However, the simulation does not converge from the beginning even with constant viscosity. I think I should learn more about MOOSE, PorousFlow, and also C++ to solve this but any suggestion from you or Chris is most welcomed. Thanks for the help.

You should be able to modify one of the tests in porous flow that use SimpleFluidProperties (as this uses a constant viscosity). If you then swap in your material with the same constant viscosity you should get the same results. If not, I guess something is incorrect in your implementation.
I'd be happy to take a look if you link to your code (although it is now night-time here so I won't look until tomorrow)

Sure. That would be great. I worked on it and this is the best that I could get. It compiles, and if I pass a constant value to viscosity1 it works. However, if I call the ParsedMaterial even with a constant value the simulation do not converge at the very beginning. Here is link to the material I wrote based on PorousFlowSingleComponentFluid, and my input file.
https://github.com/sinaomrani96/Material-property
Thanks.

You have some inconsistencies there
the computeQpProperty relies half on viscosity1, half on the fp.mu_from_p_T
These lines for example
https://github.com/sinaomrani96/Material-property/blob/09dcc35daf4f4e9bcc4203f6cd185c34642ad3b0/MyFluid.C#L78
https://github.com/sinaomrani96/Material-property/blob/09dcc35daf4f4e9bcc4203f6cd185c34642ad3b0/MyFluid.C#L97
Dear @GiudGiud, Thanks. I fixed those but still facing the same issue.

Still some problems:

AD version, you use raw_value, so you lose the derivative
non AD version, the derivatives are wrong. dmu/dP is not mu / dt, you need to compute a derivative

Yeah, as @GiudGiud said, your derivatives aren't correct.
Looking at your example input file, you want a model with 2 phases, a liquid phase (just using water properties like normal), and a gas phase where the viscosity is mu(p, S)? Is that right?

Yes I am working on the derivatives to figure it out.
It may sound a weird right now because I want to brake my problem into simpler one and solve it step by step. Considering this, It is a two phase model which has a liquid phase which has water properties on the left block and a liquid which it viscosity is mu(p, S) on the right block. So, when gas is injected from the left, the right fluid has a constant viscosity until gas reaches to the right block. I thought that maybe assigning same phase to both these liquid is the problem but as I checked this is not the reason. Also model works when a constant viscosity is assigned to the right liquid.
Sorry to make it more clear, I want the viscosity of the liquid on the right block to be dependent on the gas saturation.

Dear @GiudGiud and @cpgr,
I just wanted to give an update that the problem is now solved and the issue was the BCs. Since I was using PorousFlowPiecewiseLinearSink, and it uses the mobility I was facing the problem. When I use use_mobility = false the model works. I need more work on the BCs but in general it is fine. Thanks for your help.

node.title: Running peacock on docker installation
node.bodyText:
Hello everyone,
I am trying to run Peacock on a Docker container in my Windows 11 machine. However, I am encountering an error that says "Peacock command not found". After some investigation, it appears that the path to the Peacock executable is not included in my environment variables.
I have been trying to locate the file where I can edit the path to include the Peacock executable, but so far, I have not been successful. Could anyone provide guidance on how to locate the file or files where I can edit the path to include the correct one for Peacock?
Thank you in advance for your help.

The Peacock executable will be located here (if you followed the directions to clone moose to ~/projects/moose:
$HOME/projects/moose/python/peacock/peacock
In order to make the above path included in your PATH environment variable permanently, add the following to your shell startup profile:
Bash users:
echo "export PATH=\$PATH:\$HOME/projects/moose/python/peacock/" >> ~/.bash_profile
Zsh users:
echo "export PATH=\$PATH:\$HOME/projects/moose/python/peacock/" >> ~/.zshrc
To figure out what shell you use (Bash, Zsh, perhaps something else):
echo $0
If this returns something other than the two common shells I posted, you'll need to do some searching on the internet on how to modify your specific shell's startup profile.

node.title: Conditional Dirichlet BCs
node.bodyText:
Is there a way to apply "conditional" Dirichlet BCs to part of a side set?  For example, say I have a simulation where I only want to apply a Dirichlet condition over a location that changes as a function time (but will always be contained within a sideset on the mesh).
For a Neumann BC this type of thing is possible: just use a FunctionNeumannBC where you apply whatever BC you want in the current/active region and zero outside of that.  The zero here won't affect the problem.
But this isn't so simple for DirichletBCs, as outside the active region I want to impose no constraint on the problem, not a zero boundary condition.
The background here is that I have a simulation where I'm trying to effectively do rigid contact but using a stiff contact surface is proving to be numerically quite difficult...

There is ElementSubdomainModifier that modifies element subdomain during the simulation. I wonder if you could follow what's in there and do something similar to sidesets/nodesets. It's going to be a custom user object.

I guess the hacky way would be to subclass PenaltyDirichletBC to take a function for the penalty term.  But I suspect that's going to put me right back in convergence purgatory.  Still, I'm desperate so maybe I'll see what happens.
Let me know if it doesn't work. I can write a SidesetModifier.

Somewhat to my surprise this worked.  So the idea is to impose the Dirichlet BC with a penalty, but then use some sort of step function for the penalty stiffness so that it's only non-zero in the region you want to impose the BC.  This seems like a very specialized type of thing to do but if there's any interest in having it in the framework I'd be happy to share the code.
Hi Mark @reverendbedford, I meet almost the same situation here (Dirichlet BC on a time-varying boundary), can you share the conditional BC you wrote?
https://github.com/Argonne-National-Laboratory/deer/blob/master/src/bcs/QuasiContactBC.C

node.title: grad_test with Tri-mesh and RZ coords
node.bodyText:
Hello:
I have an app where velocity is "constant monomial" and pressure is "Lagrange first".  This is a hybrid rDG/CG scheme that works great most of the time.  But...
computeQpResidual() for the mass conservation equation (inherited from ADKernel) whose non-linear variable is pressure has:
res = _rho[_qp] * _velocity[_qp] * _grad_test[_i][_qp];
where velocity is an ADMaterialProperty(RealVectorValue) whose components are vel_x and vel_y for this 2D problem.  The problem is a simple rectangle with uniform inlet velocity and outlet pressure BCs. I have simplified the model down so there is no momentum advection, no gravity.  Just pressure gradient and form drag.
It works great when:

The mesh is all quads and the coordinate system is either XY or RZ.  No problem.
The mesh is all tris and the coord system is XY.

It does not work if the coord system is RZ and the mesh includes tris.  To make sure this wasn't an inlet BC problem, I put a quad mesh as an inlet section and have it transition to a tri-mesh.  The attached 2 figures show the velocity magnitude for both XY and RZ systems.  The velocity should be uniform (all ve_y) with a value of 0.1.  Note the higher velocity magnitude for the RZ case for the first tri at the centerline that is due to a vel_x component.  It appears that this is caused by the residual of this mass eq for the first tri element.  It should be zero but instead has a small value that forces the radial (vel_x) velocity to be non-zero.  The flow does go to a uniform distribution further downstream.
Finally, if I offset these blocks from the centerline in the RZ system, the unphysical vel_x component gradually disappears as the block is moved further away from the centerline.
Any ideas?  Help is greatly appreciated.
Joe Kelly

Hello
In RZ, there should be an extra term for the pressure gradient, just arising from the definition of the divergence in RZ
For the first component of momentum RZ, if R is the first components (usually like this)
res += -_pressure[_qp] / _ad_q_point_qp * _test[_i][_qp];
Do you have it here?
Guillaume

For XY with a mix of quads and tris, this should have worked, we would definitely need to investigate that.
Have you tried SVD, do you know how many singular values you have? This helps guessing where the issue happens

Hi Guillaume:  For the pressure gradient term, I am not integrating by parts, so I am using:
return _eps[_qp] * _grad_pressure_qp * _test[_i][_qp];
where the non-linear vars are vel_x and vel_y.  I looked at this first, but it works perfectly for quads in RZ.  I'll try svd and get back to you.  Just about done for my Saturday workday...
Joe

For this problem, I have eliminated the momentum flux terms (for debug purposes).  So, in effect, I have turned this into a Poisson problem.  With constant fluid properties, the mass eq. simply states that div(V) = 0.  The momentum eq, is simply grad(P) = -K|V|V.
At any rate, here is the SVD output for 1st iteration:
 SVD: condition number 6.229482285046e+03, 0 of 56 singular values are (nearly) zero
  SVD: smallest singular values: 1.673742906471e-04 7.262316760914e-04 1.217246675124e-03 1.653500109633e-03 2.200366856638e-03
  SVD: largest singular values : 1.000004573129e+00 1.000082403684e+00 1.000240952341e+00 1.041314956785e+00 1.042655178559e+00

I can provide the Jacobin as well.  But everything works perfectly in RZ as long as I don't use Tri's.
Joe

Is there a good reason to integrate by parts for the pressure gradient term?  I would prefer not to as I would also need the porosity gradient.  That would cause the porosity to be an auxvar instead of a material property.
As I do some more complex geometries, even with a quad mesh, albeit one that is can be slightly skewed, I begin to see a bit of striping in the pressure in RZ.  No striping in XY.

Ok in the mass equation you did integrate by parts right?
res = _rho[_qp] * _velocity[_qp] * _grad_test[_i][_qp];
this is how you got v out of the divergence and grad_test
It should have looked like integral[ 1/r d(r rho v)/dr * test * rdr ] = integral[ d(r rho v)/dr * test dr] -> int [ (r rho v) * grad_test] + boundary term
so is there a missing r factor?
Nevermind that factor comes later, multiplying the contribution to the residual
In INS and INSAD we dont integrate it by parts.
Do you compare well to INS and INSAD results for simple RZ channels?
I'm not sure why those terms are integrated by parts or not. For diffusion terms, it's to reduce the FE order required by one.
Here it may just be to make boundary terms more or less simple.

Made a mesh to investigate that.
Works fine with INS with second order velocities, first order pressure

  [inlet]
    type = CartesianMeshGenerator
    ix = 2
    iy = 4
    dim = 2
    dx = 1
    dy = 1
    subdomain_id = 2
  []

  ## add some tris
  [poly]
    type = PolyLineMeshGenerator
    points = '0.0 1.0 0.0
              0.0 2.0 0.0
              1.0 2.0 0.0
              1.0 1.0 0.0'
    loop = true
    num_edges_between_points = 2
  []
  [triang]
    type = XYDelaunayGenerator
    boundary = 'poly'
    refine_boundary = false
    desired_area = 0.2
  []
  [bot]
    type = SideSetsFromNormalsGenerator
    input = triang
    normals = '0 -1 0
               1 0 0
               -1 0 0
               0 1 0'
    new_boundary = 'bottom_tri
                    left
                    right
                    top_tri'
    replace = true
  []

  # Stitch
  [stitch]
    type = StitchedMeshGenerator
    inputs = 'inlet bot'
    stitch_boundaries_pairs = 'top bottom_tri'
    clear_stitched_boundary_ids = true
  []
  [rename_error]
    type = RenameBoundaryGenerator
    input = 'stitch'
    old_boundary = 'top'
    new_boundary = 'right'
  []
[]

Thanks for taking the time to investigate this Guillaume.  I am pretty convinced that the usual weak form of the mass advection term, namely:
res = _rho[_qp] * _velocity[_qp] * _grad_test[_i][_qp];
isn't quite perfect for RZ geometry when the velocity vars are "constant monomials" and hence essentially cell-centered finite volume vars.
I looked at INSADMass & INSMassRZ etc.  So, if one uses the strong form, then it is necessary to add the U/r term.  I thought about giving this a try but I can't use the gradient of the velocity as that is zero for monomials.
What I would really like to be able to do is use the ADDGKernel to compute the mass advection term consistent with how it is done for momentum and energy.  But my non-linear var for the mass eq. is pressure which is "Gauss first" and hence FEM.  So, I need to use CG type kernels for that.
There is probably some way to accomplish that, using DG type advection with CG, but it will take me into parts of Moose that I don't have an understanding for.  I might need to do that though when I have a good bit more time.
Thanks again for the help,
Joe

It does appear that I have a problem with skewed mesh cells, even with X-Y coords.  It really shows up when the energy eq. is turned on.  I am guessing that it is necessary for the mass/momentum/energy advection terms to all have consistent fluxes.  That is, use a DGKernel flux across the faces for all eqs.
So, the question of whether or not I can have P as a CFEM variable with others as DG (FV) is likely the real problem.  With mesh cells that are perpendicular to X-Y, the current scheme works well and avoids the checkerboard problem w/o resorting to a something like RC.
Looks like I have some work ahead of me to make this work.
Thanks again for the help.   Joe

@lindsayad thoughts?

There is probably some way to accomplish that, using DG type advection with CG

I think I agree that we d want the conservation of mass equation to look much like the conservation of momentum and energy, with the same kind of fluxes, differing only by the appropriate factor.
To do that we would need the appropriate set of test functions for that equation, maybe the same as for velocity? This seems to me like we would want to use different FE families for solution (pressure) and test functions (to write the fluxes), so a Petrov Galerkin method.

I wonder if, as an exploration, we could have the following.

add dummy nonlinear variable Z that is of the same type as velocity
use Z for the variable parameter of the mass equation, write the mass equation in a DG form
use pressure for the variable parameter of the Z equation, which is just dZ/dt = 0
This will off-course have a lot of off-diagonal terms, but a direct solver (LU with a diagonal shift for now) would handle them
